	(294, 1, '2024-01-04 08:59:08', '2024-01-04 08:59:08', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>L\'<strong>informatique</strong>&nbsp;est un domaine d\'activité&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science">scientifique</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technique">technique</a>, et&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Industrie">industriel</a>&nbsp;concernant le&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syst%C3%A8me_de_traitement_de_l%27information">traitement automatique de l\'information numérique</a>&nbsp;par l\'exécution de&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programme_informatique">programmes informatiques</a>&nbsp;hébergés par des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composant_%C3%A9lectronique">dispositifs électriques-électroniques</a>&nbsp;: des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syst%C3%A8me_embarqu%C3%A9">systèmes embarqués</a>, des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinateur">ordinateurs</a>, des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robot">robots</a>, des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automate">automates</a>,&nbsp;etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>L\'<strong>informatique</strong>&nbsp;est un domaine d\'activité&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science">scientifique</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technique">technique</a>, et&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Industrie">industriel</a>&nbsp;concernant le&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syst%C3%A8me_de_traitement_de_l%27information">traitement automatique de l\'information numérique</a>&nbsp;par l\'exécution de&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programme_informatique">programmes informatiques</a>&nbsp;hébergés par des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composant_%C3%A9lectronique">dispositifs électriques-électroniques</a>&nbsp;: des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syst%C3%A8me_embarqu%C3%A9">systèmes embarqués</a>, des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinateur">ordinateurs</a>, des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robot">robots</a>, des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automate">automates</a>,&nbsp;etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {"url":"https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x8r48b9","type":"video","providerNameSlug":"dailymotion","responsive":true,"className":"wp-embed-aspect-9-16 wp-has-aspect-ratio"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-dailymotion wp-block-embed-dailymotion wp-embed-aspect-9-16 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\nhttps://www.dailymotion.com/video/x8r48b9\n</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dailymotion</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {"url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vo1XjuLVaZo\\u0026list=PLv6GftO355AvU2fFza3iNgVscxN-aCiSf\\u0026index=26","type":"video","providerNameSlug":"youtube","responsive":true,"className":"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vo1XjuLVaZo&amp;list=PLv6GftO355AvU2fFza3iNgVscxN-aCiSf&amp;index=26\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ces champs d\'application peuvent être séparés en deux branches&nbsp;:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Informatique_th%C3%A9orique">théorique</a>&nbsp;: concerne la définition de concepts et modèles&nbsp;;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>pratique&nbsp;: s\'intéresse aux&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technique">techniques</a>&nbsp;concrètes de mise en œuvre.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:video {"id":291} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-video"><video src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/videoplayback.mp4"></video><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Video of project</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:video -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Certains domaines de l\'informatique peuvent être très&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstraction_(informatique)">abstraits</a>, comme la&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9orie_de_la_complexit%C3%A9_(informatique_th%C3%A9orique)">complexité algorithmique</a>, et d\'autres peuvent être plus proches d\'un public&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Profane">profane</a>. Ainsi, la&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9orie_des_langages">théorie des langages</a>&nbsp;demeure un domaine davantage accessible aux professionnels formés (description des&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinateur">ordinateurs</a>&nbsp;et méthodes de&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programmation_informatique">programmation</a>), tandis que les métiers liés aux&nbsp;<a href="https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interface_homme-machine">interfaces homme-machine</a>&nbsp;(IHM) sont accessibles à un plus large public.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:video {"id":291} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-video"><video controls src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/videoplayback.mp4" playsinline></video></figure>\n<!-- /wp:video -->', 'Video of project', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '289-autosave-v1', '', '', '2024-01-04 08:59:08', '2024-01-04 08:59:08', '', 289, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=294', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
	(295, 3, '2024-01-04 09:09:16', '2024-01-04 09:09:16', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> The Conditional Tags can be used in your Template files to change what content is displayed and how that content is displayed on a particular page depending on what <em>conditions</em> that page matches. For example, you might want to display a snippet of text above the series of posts, but only on the main page of your blog. With the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Conditional_Tags#The_Main_Page">is_home()</a> Conditional Tag, that task is made easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Conditional Tags can be used in your Template files to change what content is displayed and how that content is displayed on a particular page depending on what <em>conditions</em> that page matches. For example, you might want to display a snippet of text above the series of posts, but only on the main page of your blog. With the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Conditional_Tags#The_Main_Page">is_home()</a> Conditional Tag, that task is made easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {"linkTo":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped"><!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":73,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_167357615-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-73"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":75,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_149846207-e1411415781675-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-75"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":71,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_167586029-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-71"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":69,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_100830292-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-69"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Conditional Tags can be used in your Template files to change what content is displayed and how that content is displayed on a particular page depending on what <em>conditions</em> that page matches. For example, you might want to display a snippet of text above the series of posts, but only on the main page of your blog. With the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Conditional_Tags#The_Main_Page">is_home()</a> Conditional Tag, that task is made easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Conditional Tags can be used in your Template files to change what content is displayed and how that content is displayed on a particular page depending on what <em>conditions</em> that page matches. For example, you might want to display a snippet of text above the series of posts, but only on the main page of your blog. With the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Conditional_Tags#The_Main_Page">is_home()</a> Conditional Tag, that task is made easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {"columns":2,"linkTo":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-2 is-cropped"><!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":41,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","className":"is-style-rounded"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-style-rounded"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/shutterstock_146675243-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-41"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":39,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/shutterstock_124918517-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-39"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":36,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_136240700-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-36"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":35,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_180775436-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-35"/><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Model of the city</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --><figcaption class="blocks-gallery-caption wp-element-caption">Gallery of the project</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Conditional Tags can be used in your Template files to change what content is displayed and how that content is displayed on a particular page depending on what <em>conditions</em> that page matches. For example, you might want to display a snippet of text above the series of posts, but only on the main page of your blog. With the <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Conditional_Tags#The_Main_Page">is_home()</a> Conditional Tag, that task is made easy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {"linkTo":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped"><!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":36,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_136240700-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-36"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":48,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_112421816-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-48"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":34,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/shutterstock_147074498-620x350-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-34"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":30,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/shutterstock_102783866-e1398207135808-1024x809.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-30"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"lightbox":{"enabled":true},"id":53,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/shutterstock_99076997-1024x683.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-53"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->', 'Post in Gallery', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'post-in-gallery', '', '', '2024-01-08 11:55:00', '2024-01-08 11:55:00', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=295', 0, 'post', '', 2),
	(297, 1, '2024-01-05 10:01:52', '2024-01-05 10:01:52', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the following code, you can add some extra fields asking your members for their address. Just add the code t your theme’s <code>functions.php</code> file, or create a <code>functions.php</code> file if you don’t already have one.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {"url":"https://bavotasan.com/2009/adding-extra-fields-to-the-wordpress-user-profile/","type":"wp-embed","providerNameSlug":"bavotasan-com"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-wp-embed is-provider-bavotasan-com wp-block-embed-bavotasan-com"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\nhttps://bavotasan.com/2009/adding-extra-fields-to-the-wordpress-user-profile/\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->', 'Adding Extra Fields to the WordPress User Profile', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'adding-extra-fields-to-the-wordpress-user-profile', '', '', '2024-01-05 10:01:52', '2024-01-05 10:01:52', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=297', 0, 'post', '', 11),
	(298, 2, '2024-01-05 10:03:59', '2024-01-05 10:03:59', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>September 10, 2009</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since I’ve been playing around with user management a lot lately, I thought I’d share a simple technique I picked up. This technique will allow you to easily add new user profile fields that your blog’s users can use to input more information about themselves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Management of these fields will be coming in a later version of my user management plugin, but some of you may want to do this now.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this tutorial, I’ll show you how to add an input box for a Twitter username and how to display it on your site, which will look a little something like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>![/user/media/2009/09/pop-critics-profile.png](My profile and Twitter link)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want to see a live example, check out&nbsp;<a href="http://popcritics.com/2009/09/the-cw-adds-the-vampire-diaries-to-its-supernatural-lineup">one of my latests posts</a>&nbsp;on Pop Critics.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><a href="https://justintadlock.com/archives/2009/09/10/adding-and-using-custom-user-profile-fields#adding-custom-user-fields"></a>Adding custom user fields</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Open your theme’s&nbsp;<code>functions.php</code>&nbsp;file and drop this&nbsp;PHP&nbsp;code in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>add_action( \'show_user_profile\', \'my_show_extra_profile_fields\' );\nadd_action( \'edit_user_profile\', \'my_show_extra_profile_fields\' );\n\nfunction my_show_extra_profile_fields( $user ) { ?&gt;\n\n	&lt;h3&gt;Extra profile information&lt;/h3&gt;\n\n	&lt;table class="form-table"&gt;\n\n		&lt;tr&gt;\n			&lt;th&gt;&lt;label for="twitter"&gt;Twitter&lt;/label&gt;&lt;/th&gt;\n\n			&lt;td&gt;\n				&lt;input type="text" name="twitter" id="twitter" value="&lt;?php echo esc_attr( get_the_author_meta( \'twitter\', $user-&gt;ID ) ); ?&gt;" class="regular-text" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\n				&lt;span class="description"&gt;Please enter your Twitter username.&lt;/span&gt;\n			&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\n\n	&lt;/table&gt;\n&lt;?php }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will create a new area in the user edit screen that looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>![/user/media/2009/09/extra-fields.png](Additional profile fields)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The custom part of the code is this bit:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>&lt;tr&gt;\n	&lt;th&gt;&lt;label for="twitter"&gt;Twitter&lt;/label&gt;&lt;/th&gt;\n\n	&lt;td&gt;\n		&lt;input type="text" name="twitter" id="twitter" value="&lt;?php echo esc_attr( get_the_author_meta( \'twitter\', $user-&gt;ID ) ); ?&gt;" class="regular-text" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;\n		&lt;span class="description"&gt;Please enter your Twitter username.&lt;/span&gt;\n	&lt;/td&gt;\n&lt;/tr&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note that if you want to add more fields, copy that and change&nbsp;<code>twitter</code>&nbsp;to something unique for each additional field. Just make sure you change each instance of&nbsp;<code>twitter</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><a href="https://justintadlock.com/archives/2009/09/10/adding-and-using-custom-user-profile-fields#saving-the-custom-user-fields"></a>Saving the custom user fields</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Just because we’re displaying these extra fields, doesn’t mean they’ll be saved when the user profile is updated. So, we need one more function to handle this. Drop this&nbsp;PHP&nbsp;code in your theme’s&nbsp;<code>functions.php</code>&nbsp;file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>add_action( \'personal_options_update\', \'my_save_extra_profile_fields\' );\nadd_action( \'edit_user_profile_update\', \'my_save_extra_profile_fields\' );\n\nfunction my_save_extra_profile_fields( $user_id ) {\n\n	if ( !current_user_can( \'edit_user\', $user_id ) )\n		return false;\n\n	/* Copy and paste this line for additional fields. Make sure to change \'twitter\' to the field ID. */\n	update_usermeta( $user_id, \'twitter\', $_POST&#91;\'twitter\'] );\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, your information will be saved.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><a href="https://justintadlock.com/archives/2009/09/10/adding-and-using-custom-user-profile-fields#displaying-custom-user-fields-on-the-site"></a>Displaying custom user fields on the site</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For getting these additional fields, WordPress has two nifty functions:&nbsp;<code>the_author_meta()</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>get_the_author_meta()</code>. The former displays the meta information, and the latter returns it for use in&nbsp;PHP. Each takes in two parameters:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>the_author_meta( $meta_key, $user_id );\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can use this to grab the information from any of the fields you’ve created. For example, the&nbsp;<code>$meta_key</code>&nbsp;for our Twitter field is&nbsp;<code>twitter</code>. We just need to call it up somewhere in our theme.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, what we’re going to do is build an author box to add to the end of our single posts. Once again, we visit our theme’s&nbsp;<code>functions.php</code>&nbsp;file and drop some&nbsp;PHP&nbsp;code in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>function my_author_box() { ?&gt;\n	&lt;div class="author-profile vcard"&gt;\n		&lt;?php echo get_avatar( get_the_author_meta( \'user_email\' ), \'96\' ); ?&gt;\n\n		&lt;h4 class="author-name fn n"&gt;Article written by &lt;?php the_author_posts_link(); ?&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;\n\n		&lt;p class="author-description author-bio"&gt;\n			&lt;?php the_author_meta( \'description\' ); ?&gt;\n		&lt;/p&gt;\n\n		&lt;?php if ( get_the_author_meta( \'twitter\' ) ) { ?&gt;\n			&lt;p class="twitter clear"&gt;\n				&lt;a href="http://twitter.com/&lt;?php the_author_meta( \'twitter\' ); ?&gt;" title="Follow &lt;?php the_author_meta( \'display_name\' ); ?&gt; on Twitter"&gt;Follow &lt;?php the_author_meta( \'display_name\' ); ?&gt; on Twitter&lt;/a&gt;\n			&lt;/p&gt;\n		&lt;?php } // End check for twitter ?&gt;\n	&lt;/div&gt;&lt;?php\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, all you need to do call the function in your theme’s&nbsp;<code>single.php</code>&nbsp;file somewhere after the post has been displayed:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>&lt;?php my_author_box(); ?&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’re using a child theme, your theme author can probably tell you a more appropriate action hook to add this function to so you don’t mess up your theme’s template files.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Adding and using custom user profile fields', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'adding-and-using-custom-user-profile-fields', '', '', '2024-01-05 10:05:39', '2024-01-05 10:05:39', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=298', 0, 'post', '', 1),
