	(335, 1, '2024-01-12 07:39:15', '2024-01-12 07:39:15', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>link : https://wptangtoc.com/toi-uu-may-do-suc-manh-cua-password-trong-wordpress/</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Làm theo các bước dưới đây để tắt Máy đo độ mạnh mật khẩu. Điều này sẽ xóa nó khỏi các trang không cần thiết trong WordPress và WooCommerce. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>add_action(\'wp_print_scripts\', \'wptangtoc_toi_uu_auto_kiem_tra_suc_manh_wp\', 100);</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>function wptangtoc_toi_uu_auto_kiem_tra_suc_manh_wp() {<br>global $wp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>$WordPress_check = isset($wp-&gt;query_vars&#91;\'lost-password\']) || (isset($_GET&#91;\'action\']) &amp;&amp; $_GET&#91;\'action\'] === \'lostpassword\') || is_page(\'lost_password\');\n\n$woocommerce_check = (class_exists(\'WooCommerce\') &amp;&amp; (is_account_page() || is_checkout()));\n\nif(!$WordPress_check &amp;&amp; !$woocommerce_check) {\n    if(wp_script_is(\'zxcvbn-async\', \'enqueued\')) {\n        wp_dequeue_script(\'zxcvbn-async\');\n    }\n\n    if(wp_script_is(\'password-strength-meter\', \'enqueued\')) {\n        wp_dequeue_script(\'password-strength-meter\');\n    }\n\n    if(wp_script_is(\'wc-password-strength-meter\', \'enqueued\')) {\n        wp_dequeue_script(\'wc-password-strength-meter\');\n    }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bạn hãy cho đoạn code này vào file&nbsp;<code>functions.php</code>&nbsp;của bạn.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Như vậy là xong.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Khắc phục sự cố Máy đo độ mạnh mật khẩu<br>Nếu bạn đã tắt đồng hồ đo độ mạnh mật khẩu và vẫn nhìn thấy các tập lệnh, rất có thể đó là do themes WordPress của bạn, các lập trình viên họ tích hợp sẵn vào đó vì đơn giản bạn sử dụng trang đăng nhập overlay lightbox ví như themes flatsome…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>nếu bạn có một liên kết đăng nhập khởi tạo cửa sổ popup overlay bật lên trên trang web của mình, nhà phát triển lập trình viên themes thường sẽ tải tập lệnh biểu mẫu đăng nhập ở chân trang của trang web.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Điều này có nghĩa là mọi trang trên trang web thương mại điện tử của bạn về mặt kỹ thuật được coi là một trang tài khoản và do đó các tập lệnh của máy đo mật khẩu đều tải.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dưới đây là một số giải pháp, mình sẽ đưa ra 2 giải pháp một là cách dễ làm và một cách khó làm.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cách dễ làm: Nếu chủ đề WordPress của bạn có tùy chọn vô hiệu hóa đăng nhập popup overlay bật lên và thay vào đó đưa người dùng đến một trang riêng biệt ( đăng nhập bằng liên kết link), đây thường là cách tốt nhất và dễ nhất.( bạn cứ thấy trang thương mai điện khủng ở việt nam như shopee, lazada, dienmayxanh… ít khi có ông nào sử dụng kiểu dạng popup đăng nhập cả, ngoài trừ ông tiki họ làm rất tốt và đặc biệt)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cách khó làm: nếu như bạn vẫn muốn popup đăng nhập thì nếu như bạn có trình độ về javascript và ajax hoặc bạn có thể thuê một lập trình viên nào đó ( lập trình viên này cũng phải có trình độ cao đấy nhé) yêu cầu họ khi người dùng click vào from đăng nhập hay icon nút đăng nhập gì đó tập lệnh mới được chạy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tóm tắt:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Hãy cố gắng đặt cho mình những mật WordPress dài và mạnh khó khăn để nâng cao bảo mật, chắc bạn biết điều đó là lợi như thế nào.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nếu bạn hiểu biết về php, giả sử bạn không sử dụng plugin wooCommerce thì bạn có thể loại bỏ chúng ra, hoặc website của bạn không có cái gì gọi là đăng nhập thì loại bỏ hết câu điều kiện if đi cũng được như vậy là tốt nhất.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nếu trong trường hợp bạn không biết gì về php, giả sử bạn không sử dụng plugin wooCommerce thì bạn cứ cho đoạn code này cũng được chả sao vẫn rất ổn.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>chắc mình phải code thêm đoạn những ai như mình là trang web cơ bản blog không ai đăng nhập gì hết thì bạn sử dụng đoạn code này file <code>functions.php</code> của bạn</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":337,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-7.png" alt="" class="wp-image-337"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Đoạn code trên dành cho những ai không sử dụng trang đăng nhập dạng blog cơ bản như mình, ghi chú là nếu bạn đã dùng đoạn code này rồi thì không nên dùng đoạn code trên nhé và ngược lại nhé ( tránh bị xung đột)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Hướng dẫn tắt máy đo độ mạnh mật khẩu', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'huong-dan-tat-may-do-do-manh-mat-khau', '', '', '2024-01-12 07:41:19', '2024-01-12 07:41:19', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=335', 0, 'post', '', 0),
	(336, 1, '2024-01-12 07:40:28', '2024-01-12 07:40:28', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>link : https://wptangtoc.com/toi-uu-may-do-suc-manh-cua-password-trong-wordpress/</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Làm theo các bước dưới đây để tắt Máy đo độ mạnh mật khẩu. Điều này sẽ xóa nó khỏi các trang không cần thiết trong WordPress và WooCommerce. add_action(\'wp_print_scripts\', \'wptangtoc_toi_uu_auto_kiem_tra_suc_manh_wp\', 100); function wptangtoc_toi_uu_auto_kiem_tra_suc_manh_wp() { global $wp; $WordPress_check = isset($wp-&gt;query_vars[\'lost-password\']) || (isset($_GET[\'action\']) &amp;&amp; $_GET[\'action\'] === \'lostpassword\') || is_page(\'lost_password\'); $woocommerce_check = (class_exists(\'WooCommerce\') &amp;&amp; (is_account_page() || is_checkout())); if(!$WordPress_check &amp;&amp; !$woocommerce_check) { if(wp_script_is(\'zxcvbn-async\', \'enqueued\')) { wp_dequeue_script(\'zxcvbn-async\'); } if(wp_script_is(\'password-strength-meter\', \'enqueued\')) { wp_dequeue_script(\'password-strength-meter\'); } if(wp_script_is(\'wc-password-strength-meter\', \'enqueued\')) { wp_dequeue_script(\'wc-password-strength-meter\'); } } }</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bạn hãy cho đoạn code này vào file&nbsp;<code>functions.php</code>&nbsp;của bạn.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Như vậy là xong.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Khắc phục sự cố Máy đo độ mạnh mật khẩu<br>Nếu bạn đã tắt đồng hồ đo độ mạnh mật khẩu và vẫn nhìn thấy các tập lệnh, rất có thể đó là do themes WordPress của bạn, các lập trình viên họ tích hợp sẵn vào đó vì đơn giản bạn sử dụng trang đăng nhập overlay lightbox ví như themes flatsome…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>nếu bạn có một liên kết đăng nhập khởi tạo cửa sổ popup overlay bật lên trên trang web của mình, nhà phát triển lập trình viên themes thường sẽ tải tập lệnh biểu mẫu đăng nhập ở chân trang của trang web.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Điều này có nghĩa là mọi trang trên trang web thương mại điện tử của bạn về mặt kỹ thuật được coi là một trang tài khoản và do đó các tập lệnh của máy đo mật khẩu đều tải.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dưới đây là một số giải pháp, mình sẽ đưa ra 2 giải pháp một là cách dễ làm và một cách khó làm.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cách dễ làm: Nếu chủ đề WordPress của bạn có tùy chọn vô hiệu hóa đăng nhập popup overlay bật lên và thay vào đó đưa người dùng đến một trang riêng biệt ( đăng nhập bằng liên kết link), đây thường là cách tốt nhất và dễ nhất.( bạn cứ thấy trang thương mai điện khủng ở việt nam như shopee, lazada, dienmayxanh… ít khi có ông nào sử dụng kiểu dạng popup đăng nhập cả, ngoài trừ ông tiki họ làm rất tốt và đặc biệt)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cách khó làm: nếu như bạn vẫn muốn popup đăng nhập thì nếu như bạn có trình độ về javascript và ajax hoặc bạn có thể thuê một lập trình viên nào đó ( lập trình viên này cũng phải có trình độ cao đấy nhé) yêu cầu họ khi người dùng click vào from đăng nhập hay icon nút đăng nhập gì đó tập lệnh mới được chạy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tóm tắt:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Hãy cố gắng đặt cho mình những mật WordPress dài và mạnh khó khăn để nâng cao bảo mật, chắc bạn biết điều đó là lợi như thế nào.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nếu bạn hiểu biết về php, giả sử bạn không sử dụng plugin wooCommerce thì bạn có thể loại bỏ chúng ra, hoặc website của bạn không có cái gì gọi là đăng nhập thì loại bỏ hết câu điều kiện if đi cũng được như vậy là tốt nhất.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nếu trong trường hợp bạn không biết gì về php, giả sử bạn không sử dụng plugin wooCommerce thì bạn cứ cho đoạn code này cũng được chả sao vẫn rất ổn.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>chắc mình phải code thêm đoạn những ai như mình là trang web cơ bản blog không ai đăng nhập gì hết thì bạn sử dụng đoạn code này file <code>functions.php</code> của bạn</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Đoạn code trên dành cho những ai không sử dụng trang đăng nhập dạng blog cơ bản như mình, ghi chú là nếu bạn đã dùng đoạn code này rồi thì không nên dùng đoạn code trên nhé và ngược lại nhé ( tránh bị xung đột)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Hướng dẫn tắt máy đo độ mạnh mật khẩu', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '335-autosave-v1', '', '', '2024-01-12 07:40:28', '2024-01-12 07:40:28', '', 335, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=336', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
	(337, 1, '2024-01-12 07:40:29', '2024-01-12 07:40:29', '', 'image-7', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'image-7', '', '', '2024-01-12 07:40:29', '2024-01-12 07:40:29', '', 335, 'http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-7.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
	(338, 1, '2024-01-12 09:50:27', '2024-01-12 09:50:27', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Website của bạn sẽ càng trở nên chân thực và tin cậy hơn khi sở hữu những thông tin thực. Một trong số những thông tin mang đến "điểm cộng" chân thực cho doanh nghiệp chính là địa điểm. Khách hàng luôn cảm thấy an tâm hơn biết chính xác vị trí của bạn trên Google Maps - bản đồ trực tuyến có lượng người dùng lớn hàng đầu. Qua bài viết sau, Mắt Bão sẽ mách bạn các cách chèn Google Maps vào Website WordPress.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":339,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-8.png" alt="" class="wp-image-339"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>MỤC LỤC</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href="https://www.matbao.net/tin-tuc/bat-mi-cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-93861.html#tai-sao-can-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress"><em><strong>Tại sao cần chèn Google Maps vào Website WordPress?</strong></em></a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href="https://www.matbao.net/tin-tuc/bat-mi-cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-93861.html#huong-dan-tao-google-maps-api-key"><em><strong>Hướng dẫn tạo Google Maps API key</strong></em></a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href="https://www.matbao.net/tin-tuc/bat-mi-cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-93861.html#cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress"><em><strong>Cách chèn Google Maps vào Website WordPress</strong></em></a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong><a></a>Tại sao cần chèn Google Maps vào Website WordPress?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Như đã đề cập ở mở đầu, việc thêm Google Maps vào website sẽ khiến khách hàng tin tưởng doanh nghiệp nói chung. Sau đây Mắt Bão sẽ liệt kê một số lý do nữa mà bạn nên thêm Google Maps vào website ngay hôm nay:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Có tính tương tác cao, khách truy cập có thể di chuyển xung quanh bản đồ&nbsp;để định vị tốt hơn.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Bạn có thể dùng Google Maps để làm nổi bật một hoặc nhiều vị trí bạn muốn.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Khách truy cập có thể có thể dễ dàng chuyển bản đồ tới điện thoại, lưu lại hướng dẫn chỉ đường trên điện thoại.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Thêm Google Maps vào website cũng là một tiêu chí khi SEO Local cho doanh nghiệp. Nhờ vào SEO Local, thứ hạng của website khi khách hàng ở khu vực liền kề tìm kiếm cũng tăng cao.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Để cụ thể hơn, Mắt Bão sẽ khái quát cho bạn khái niệm về SEO Local là gì?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>SEO Local là quá trình tối ưu hóa website dựa trên các từ khóa liên quan đến một địa phương, vùng miền cụ thể</strong>. Mục đích tăng khả năng nhận diện đối với sự hiện diện của thương hiệu trên Internet khi tìm kiếm thông tin về địa phương đó.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mời bạn tham khảo Video dưới đây để biết cách thêm Google Maps vào Blogger hoặc Website WordPress: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {"url":"https://youtu.be/3nhsAfm81po","type":"video","providerNameSlug":"youtube","responsive":true,"className":"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\nhttps://youtu.be/3nhsAfm81po\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Hướng dẫn tạo Google Maps API key</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Đầu tiên, chúng ta cần phải có API để có thể sử dụng được Google Maps. Sau đây tôi xin hướng dẫn các bạn các bước tạo&nbsp;Google API để sử dụng cho&nbsp;<strong>Google Maps</strong>&nbsp;theo&nbsp;<strong>tên miên riêng</strong>&nbsp;của bạn một cách hiệu quả nhất.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 1</strong>: Truy cập:&nbsp;<a href="https://console.developers.google.com/"><strong>https://console.developers.google.com/</strong></a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 2</strong>: Click vào Select a project để tạo mới project. Một&nbsp;project có thể chứa nhiểu API. Một&nbsp;API có thể dùng cho nhiều website, tùy thuộc vào cài đặt của các bạn. Các bước như hình sau:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-5.png" alt="Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress. Click vào Select a project để tạo mới project"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-6.png" alt="Click vào Select a project để tạo mới project. Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 3</strong>: Điền đầy đủ thông tin rồi ấn&nbsp;<strong>Create</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-7.png" alt="Click vào Select a project để tạo mới project. Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 4</strong>: Sau khi Create xong hãy chọn lại project bạn vừa tạo. rồi làm theo các bước khi trong hình</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-8.png" alt="Click vào Select a project để tạo mới project. Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 5</strong>: Tại đây bạn đã có API mà bạn cần. hãy copy nó để sử dụng. Ấn Restrict Key để tiếp tục cài đặt</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-9.png" alt="Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress, lấy Google API như thế nào?"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 6</strong>: Tại đây hãy điền tên cho API để sau này bạn biết nó dùng cho web nào hay ứng dụng nào. Chọn&nbsp;<strong>Http referrers</strong>&nbsp;(web sites) như hình và điền tên miền của bạn vào theo định dạng *.your-domain.com/* và http://your-domain.com/* =&gt; sau đó ấn Save để lưu thông tin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-10.png" alt="Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress, lấy Google API như thế nào?"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 7</strong>: Bước này khá quan trọng. Bước này để enable thư viện nào mà API được phép sử dụng. Chúng ta sẽ Enable những như viện sau:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Google Maps JavaScript API</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Google Maps Directions API</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Google Maps Embed API</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Google Maps Geocoding API</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Google Places API Web Service</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-11.png" alt="Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress, lấy Google API như thế nào?"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bước 8</strong>: Sau khi Enable xong sang tab Dashboard sẽ được như hình</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-12.png" alt="Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress, lấy Google API như thế nào?"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Như vậy, chúng ta đã hoàn tất qui trình khởi tạo Google Maps API, chúc các bạn thành công.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-api-keys-13.png" alt="Cách chèn Google Maps vào WordPress, lấy Google API như thế nào?"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong><a></a>Cách chèn Google Maps vào Website WordPress</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ở phần này, Mắt Bão sẽ chỉ bạn cách chèn google map vào WordPress&nbsp;với 3 cách khác nhau:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cài Plugin WordPress&nbsp;Google Maps.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Nhúng code Google Maps vào website.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Sử dụng WordPress theme.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><em><strong>Sử dụng plugin WordPress để chèn&nbsp;Google Maps</strong></em></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-1.jpg" alt="Plugin WP Google Maps trên WordPress"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Plugin WP Google Maps trên WordPress</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Với&nbsp;<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-google-maps/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank"><em><strong>WP Google Maps</strong></em></a>, bạn có thể chèn bản đồ vào trang qua shortcode. Hơn nữa, plugin này cũng giúp bạn tùy chỉnh map markers, thiết kế, thích nghi với các Plugin Cache cũng như CDN.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ngoài ra,&nbsp;<em><strong><a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wd-google-maps/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Plugin WD Google Maps</a></strong></em>&nbsp;cũng là lựa chọn xứng đáng với sự chú ý của bạn khi nói về việc thêm Google Maps vào WordPress. Đặc biệt với WD Google Maps, bạn có thể khiến cho bản đồ bạn thêm vào thân thiện trên các thiết bị khác nhau.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Một cái tên khác không thể không nhắc đến chính là&nbsp;<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/google-maps-widget/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank"><em><strong>Google Maps Widget</strong></em></a>. Plugin nàu giúp thêm bản đồ dưới dạng Thumbnail để chèn vào sidebar hay Footer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bạn hoàn toàn có thể trải nghiệp hết tất cả các Plugins này để tìm thấy được công cụ phù hợp với nhu cầu của mình.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->\n<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><em><strong>Cách chèn Google Maps vào website WordPress sử dụng Plugin WP Google Maps</strong></em></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Đầu tiên bạn cần thêm Plugin này vào WordPress bằng cách vào&nbsp;<strong>Plugins&nbsp;› Add New</strong>. Hãy tìm kiếm Plugin WP Google Maps, nhấn nút Install Now để cài đặt.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sau khi cài đặt, tại thanh công cụ WordPress bạn sẽ thấy có tab tên&nbsp;<strong>Maps</strong>. Lúc này bạn đã hoàn toàn có thể cài đặt Google Maps vào website của mình.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-2.jpg" alt="Sau khi cài đặt Plugin WP Google Maps thành công"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Sau khi cài đặt Plugin WP Google Maps thành công</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ở trang kế tiếp, plugin sẽ thông báo bạn cần&nbsp;một&nbsp;<strong>Google API key</strong>. Hãy dán API key bạn lấy được ở Mục trên vào nơi plugin yêu cầu.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/uploads/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-3.jpg" alt="Nơi dán Key API của Google Maps"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Nơi dán Key API của Google Maps</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Để chỉnh sửa và sử dụng trên website, nhấn vào nút&nbsp;<strong>Edit&nbsp;</strong>bên dưới tên map. Giờ plugin sẽ hỏi bạn nền tảng nào bạn muốn dùng bản đồ. Hãy chọn&nbsp;<strong>Google Maps</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-4.png" alt="Hãy chọn nền tảng Google Maps"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-5.jpg" alt="Hãy chọn nền tảng Google Maps"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Hãy chọn nền tảng Google Maps</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tại đây hãy thiết lập đơn giản&nbsp;<strong>Map Types</strong>,&nbsp;sử dụng&nbsp;<strong>Classic Roadmaps</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-6.jpg" alt="Tại đây hãy thiết lập đơn giản bằng cách sử dụng Classic Roadmaps. "/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sau đó là phần Markers, bạn hoàn toàn có thể di chuyển vị trí của mình dựa vào tọa độ GPS hoặc tự mình đánh dấu trên bản đồ.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sau đó tới phần&nbsp;<strong>Animation</strong>&nbsp;cho bản đồ. Nếu bạn muốn thêm hiệu ứng nảy lên của bản đồ, hãy dùng hiệu ứng Bounce. Bạn cũng có thể tùy chỉnh bản đồ Google để hiển thị ô pop-up ngay kế bên marker để nhập địa chỉ đầy đủ.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-7.png" alt="Chọn vị trí của doanh nghiệp trên Google Maps"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Chọn vị trí của doanh nghiệp trên Google Maps</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Khi bạn đã hoàn tất, nhấn vào nút&nbsp;<strong>Save Marker&nbsp;</strong>để tải lại trang. Sau đó nhấn nút&nbsp;<strong>Save Map&nbsp;</strong>chính giữa màn hình, plugin sẽ lưu toàn bộ thay đổi.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bạn cũng có thể nhúng google map vào website bằng cách&nbsp;dán shortcode.&nbsp;Để lấy shortcode của bản đồ, hãy vào trong tab&nbsp;<strong>Maps</strong>. Bạn sẽ thấy nó ở ngay cạnh tên bản đồ.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-8.jpg" alt="Cách lấy Shortcode của bản đồ"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Như bạn thấy việc sử dụng Plugin WP Google Maps để thêm bản đồ là cực kỳ dễ dàng. Ở phần tiếp theo Mắt Bão sẽ hướng dẫn bạn thêm Google Maps vào Blogger hay Website WordPress bằng Embed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><em><strong>Cách thêm Google Maps vào Blogger hay Website WordPress bằng Embed</strong></em></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bước 1: Bạn có thể dùng&nbsp;<strong><a href="https://www.embedgooglemap.net/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Embed Google Map</a></strong>&nbsp;để code bằng giao diện mặc định của Google Maps. Nó sẽ giúp bạn thiết lập kích thước và tỉ lệ. Bạn chỉ cần nhập địa chỉ vào phần&nbsp;<strong>Enter Your Address</strong>&nbsp;là được.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-embed-1.jpg" alt="Bạn hoàn toàn có thể gắn Google Maps vào website bằng cách thêm code thông thường"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Bạn hoàn toàn có thể gắn Google Maps vào website bằng cách thêm code thông thường</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bước 2: Nhấn nút nút&nbsp;<strong>Get HTML-Code&nbsp;</strong>để site này tạo ra code&nbsp;<strong>HTML code snippet</strong>&nbsp;của Maps để bạn tự chèn vào website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-embed-2.png" alt="Bạn hoàn toàn có thể gắn Google Maps vào website bằng cách thêm code thông thường"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bước 3: Copy đoạn code ở trên, sau đó quay lại WordPress dashboard. Rồi mở editor (soạn thảo bài viết) và thêm vào code của bài viết này. Nhấn vào ô&nbsp;<strong>Text</strong>, dán code HTML của Google Maps vào vị trí cần thiết rồi lưu lại thay đổi:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-embed-3.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Kiểm tra xem&nbsp;<strong>Google Maps</strong>&nbsp;đã được nhúng lên website chưa. Nếu có lỗi xảy ra, hãy kiểm tra lại code khi thêm vào để đảm bảo không có lỗi code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-embed-4.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><em><strong>Sử dụng WordPress Theme để chèn Google Maps</strong></em></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>WordPress Google Maps</strong>&nbsp;phổ biến đến độ có nhiều themes đã kích hoạt sẵn chức năng này mặc định. Nếu bạn dùng theme đúng, bạn không cần cài plugin hay dùng HTML code để chèn bản đồ. Thường các&nbsp;<strong>theme premium</strong>&nbsp;đều hỗ trợ tính năng này, nên có thể bạn sẽ mất ít phí. Tuy nhiên các theme này thường có giá thành không rẻ vì chúng còn được tích hợp nhiều tính năng khác. Hãy cân nhắc kỹ trước khi mua theme về sử dụng nhé!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.matbao.net/appupload/news/trilm/images/cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress-dibi.jpg" alt="Theme WordPress Divi"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Theme WordPress Divi</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Một trong các theme nổi bật nhất hiện nay có kèm theo tính năng này là&nbsp;<a href="https://www.elegantthemes.com/gallery/divi/"><strong>Divi</strong></a>. Việc thêm API của Google Maps cũng khá đơn giản, chỉ cần nhập mã API vào và theme sẽ giúp bạn làm phần còn lại.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Hy vọng qua bài viết này, Mắt Bão đã có thể sơ lược cho bạn những lý do tại sao website của bạn cần có nhúng Google Maps cũng như đã hướng dẫn thành công cách thêm Google Maps vào website WordPress của bạn. Về mặt kỹ thuật, Mắt Bão vẫn khuyên bạn nên sử dụng các gói&nbsp;<a href="https://www.matbao.net/hosting/cloud-wordpress-hosting.html"><strong>Hosting WordPress</strong></a>&nbsp;có bao gồm tư vấn kỹ thuật. Sẽ không có gì tuyệt vời hơn khi mọi nhu cầu chỉnh sửa website của bạn đều có người hỗ trợ và tư vấn kỹ thuật "tận răng" cho mình đúng chứ!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Bật mí cách chèn Google Maps vào Website WordPress', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bat-mi-cach-chen-google-maps-vao-website-wordpress', '', '', '2024-01-12 09:50:27', '2024-01-12 09:50:27', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=338', 0, 'post', '', 0),
	(339, 1, '2024-01-12 09:47:32', '2024-01-12 09:47:32', '', 'image-8', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'image-8', '', '', '2024-01-12 09:47:32', '2024-01-12 09:47:32', '', 338, 'http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-8.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
	(340, 1, '2024-01-12 10:34:50', '2024-01-12 10:34:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>[wpgmza id="1"]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Contact', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'contact', '', '', '2024-01-12 12:20:22', '2024-01-12 12:20:22', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?page_id=340', 0, 'page', '', 0),
	(341, 1, '2024-01-12 10:35:28', '2024-01-12 10:35:28', ' ', '', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', '341', '', '', '2024-01-12 10:35:28', '2024-01-12 10:35:28', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=341', 16, 'nav_menu_item', '', 0),
	(342, 1, '2024-01-12 10:42:56', '2024-01-12 10:42:56', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are two ways to create a user registration form in WordPress: with or without a plugin. Here’s a brief look at both of the&nbsp;methods:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-1-the-default-user-registration-feature-in-wordpress">1. The Default User Registration Feature in WordPress&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lucky for you, WordPress already comes with a default user registration feature. You can find a widget called&nbsp;<strong>Meta</strong>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;<strong>Appearance</strong>&nbsp;section of your WordPress dashboard.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All you have to do is create a meta widget. It’ll automatically generate a module with links to the registration and login page. Following these links, your users can register themselves easily.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The meta widget can be placed in the footer or header depending on the layout of the WordPress theme you’re using.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Pros:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>You don’t have to create a registration or login form yourself.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>No need for third-party plugins or services to build a registration form.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Cons:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>There’s no easy way to customize the login and registration form.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>You cannot add more form fields other than the default WordPress user fields.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For more details, please check our full guide on building&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/create-wordpress-user-registration-form-without-plugin/">registration forms without a plugin</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-2-using-a-wordpress-user-registration-plugin">2. Using a WordPress User Registration Plugin&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next method is to create a custom WordPress user registration form with the help of a&nbsp;<a href="https://everestforms.net/blog/what-is-a-wordpress-plugin/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">plugin</a>. Luckily, there are plenty of&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/best-free-wordpress-registration-plugins/">registration plugins in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A WordPress registration plugin helps you build registration forms and add them to your website. This way, users can fill in their details and submit the form to complete the registration.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That’s not all. You can also assign user roles directly from the registration form settings.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This evidently makes your job much easier as the site owner. Moreover, a lot of these registration plugins allow you to manage your user entries too. You can also integrate features like anti-spam protection to prevent spam bots and malicious registrations on your site.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->\n<h4 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-what-s-the-best-wordpress-user-registration-plugin">What’s the Best WordPress User Registration Plugin?</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There’s no reason why one should not use a WordPress user registration plugin with all&nbsp;these benefits. And the best option you can find is&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/">User Registration</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5084} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/1-user-registration-plugin.png" alt="User Registration WordPress Plugin" class="wp-image-5084"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s a WordPress user registration form plugin that allows you to create custom registration forms effortlessly with its drag and drop builder. Because of the user-friendly interface, even beginners can create amazing user registration forms in just a few minutes.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even more beginner-friendly is the default form and sample registration plus account page you get upon installing this plugin. Just configure the settings and publish the form on your website.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not to mention, it provides full support for WooCommerce. It helps small businesses to&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/woocommerce-registration-form/">create WooCommerce registration forms</a>&nbsp;with extra fields, collect user information, and provide their users easy and quick checkout. That makes it the&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/best-woocommerce-registration-form-plugins/">best WoCommerce registration plugin</a>&nbsp;on the market!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That’s just the tip of the iceberg. We’ve highlighted more reasons&nbsp;why you should choose the User Registration plugin:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Custom form fields&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Beautiful My Account page&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In-built login form&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Assign user roles and capabilities&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Customize front-end messages&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Export and import forms as JSON files&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Send&nbsp;<a href="https://everestforms.net/features/email-notifications/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">confirmation emails</a>&nbsp;after registration</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Google&nbsp;reCaptcha&nbsp;for&nbsp;<a href="https://everestforms.net/blog/block-contact-form-spam-wordpress/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">anti-spam protection</a>&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Pricing:</strong>&nbsp;The User Registration plugin is available for free in the WordPress repository. If you’re interested in the premium version, the cheapest plan starts at just $99 per year.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That’s why we’ll be guiding you through the process of creating a WordPress user registration form using the User Registration plugin. Without further ado, let’s get into it!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-1-how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress-easy-method">#1. How to Create a User Registration Form in WordPress? (Easy Method)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember how we talked about User Registration’s default form and sample pages? In this section, you’ll learn how to use the default form and sample pages to quickly add a registration form to your website.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-1-enable-users-to-register-on-your-website-with-a-front-end-form">Step 1. Enable Users to Register on Your Website (with a Front-end Form)&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first thing you need to do is enable users to register on your website using a form. This option is turned off by default.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To turn it on, go to Settings on your WordPress dashboard. Then, look for the&nbsp;<strong>Membership</strong>&nbsp;option under&nbsp;<strong>General</strong>&nbsp;settings. To allow users to register from a front-end form, tick the&nbsp;<strong>Anyone can register&nbsp;</strong>option.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5085} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/2-membership.png" alt="Enable Membership" class="wp-image-5085"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once that’s done, scroll down to&nbsp;<strong>New User Default Role</strong>&nbsp;and set it as&nbsp;<strong>Subscriber</strong>. You can choose other roles depending on the permissions you want to grant to the users. However, be careful about which user role to set as default to avoid misuse of access.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5086} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/3-default-user-role.png" alt="User Default Role for Registration Forms" class="wp-image-5086"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, you can&nbsp;<strong>Save Changes</strong>&nbsp;and proceed to the next step.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":3376} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/savechangesbutton.png" alt="Save Changes Button" class="wp-image-3376"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-2-download-and-install-the-user-registration-plugin">Step 2. Download and Install the User Registration Plugin&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Of course, you’ll first have to download and install the user registration plugin before you do anything else. So, download the plugin from&nbsp;<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/user-registration/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">here</a>. It will be saved as a zip file on your device.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After that, open your dashboard again. In the&nbsp;<strong>Plugins</strong>&nbsp;section, click on&nbsp;<strong>Add New</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5089} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/5-add-new-plugin.png" alt="Add New Plugin" class="wp-image-5089"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, you can simply search for the plugin and install it directly once you find it.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5092} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/8-alternative-install.png" alt="Search User Registration Plugin" class="wp-image-5092"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Make sure you activate the plugin as well.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5091} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/7-activate-plugin.png" alt="Activate User Registration Plugin" class="wp-image-5091"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Alternatively, you can use the upload method. It’s useful if you’ve already downloaded the plugin file on your local computer. It’s mainly the case if you purchased the premium version of the plugin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To install from this method, click on the&nbsp;<strong>Upload Plugin</strong>&nbsp;option and then select the plugin file in .zip format and click&nbsp;<strong>Install Now</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5090} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/6-install-plugin.png" alt="Upload Plugin" class="wp-image-5090"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After that, you need to activate the plugin and enter the license keys if you installed the premium version. You can find the license keys in your account area in on plugin store WPEverest.com.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-3-install-sample-pages-by-the-plugin">Step 3. Install Sample Pages by the Plugin&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next place the setup process takes you to is the&nbsp;<strong>Installed Plugins</strong>&nbsp;under the&nbsp;<strong>Plugins</strong>&nbsp;tab. Here, you can see that the User Registration plugin is now active on your website. The most important thing, however, is to&nbsp;<strong>Install User Registration Pages</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5093} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/9-install-pages.png" alt="Install Sample Pages" class="wp-image-5093"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you hit that button, you get two sample pages on your website: My Account and Registration.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5094} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/10-new-pages.png" alt="Sample Pages" class="wp-image-5094"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>My Account:</strong>&nbsp;The&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/create-user-profile-page-in-wordpress/">user profile page</a>&nbsp;that each registered user can access after logging in.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Registration:</strong>&nbsp;The WordPress page that displays the&nbsp;<strong>Default Form</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But, where’s the&nbsp;<strong>Default Form</strong>? We’ll discuss just that in the next step.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-4-find-the-default-form-and-configure-settings">Step 4. Find the Default Form and Configure Settings&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You’ll find a default user registration form right in the User Registration tab. It’s the perfect solution for people who want a simple form without making everything from scratch.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5095} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/11-default-form.png" alt="Default Form" class="wp-image-5095"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The form consists of 4 form fields: Username, User Email, User Password, and Confirm Password.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5096} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/12-form-fields.png" alt="Preview Form" class="wp-image-5096"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can check how it will look in the front end with the&nbsp;<strong>Preview</strong>&nbsp;button.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5097} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/13-preview.png" alt="Default User Registration Form Preview" class="wp-image-5097"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember that it might look different for you based on what theme you’re currently using on your website.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, all that’s remaining to do is configure the settings for this form. To do that, go to&nbsp;<strong>General Settings</strong>&nbsp;under&nbsp;<strong>Form Setting</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5098} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/14-form-setting.png" alt="User Registration Form Setting" class="wp-image-5098"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let us explain each setting, in brief, to help you out.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>User login option:</strong>&nbsp;Choose the criteria for login after registration. This can be manual login, automatic login, email confirmation, or admin approval.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Default User Role:</strong>&nbsp;Assign a specific user role to all the members who register using this particular form.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Enable Strong Password:</strong>&nbsp;Enabling this feature means the form asks users for a strong password while registering.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Redirect URL:</strong>&nbsp;Decide which page the user ends up in after successful user registration.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Form Submit Button Custom Class:</strong>&nbsp;Create custom CSS class for the submit button. In the case of multiple classes, separate each class by a&nbsp;comma&nbsp;(,).&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Form Submit Button Label:</strong>&nbsp;Type in your own label for the submit button like “Register.”&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Success message position:</strong>&nbsp;You can place the success message either at the top or bottom.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Enable&nbsp;reCaptcha&nbsp;Support:</strong>&nbsp;Enable Google&nbsp;reCaptcha&nbsp;in your registration form for anti-spam protection.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Form Template:</strong>&nbsp;Select a template for your form from these five options: Default, Bordered, Flat, Rounded, and Rounded Edge.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Custom CSS class:</strong>&nbsp;This section allows you to add custom CSS classes for your registration form.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, configure the default form according to your requirements, and it’s ready to be used in your WordPress website.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-5-show-the-registration-page-on-your-website">Step 5. Show the Registration Page on Your Website&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, you can display the Registration page on your menu or footer, which will lead your users to the default registration form.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To do this, navigate to the&nbsp;<strong>Menus</strong>&nbsp;section of&nbsp;<strong>Appearance</strong>. First, create a new menu in&nbsp;<strong>Menu Structure</strong>&nbsp;by giving it a name and pressing&nbsp;<strong>Create Menu</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5099} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/15-menu.png" alt="Create Menu" class="wp-image-5099"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then, select&nbsp;<strong>Registration</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>My Account</strong>&nbsp;from the&nbsp;<strong>Add menu items</strong>&nbsp;box. Then, click&nbsp;<strong>Add to Menu</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5100} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/16-add-pages.png" alt="Add to Menu" class="wp-image-5100"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After that, select&nbsp;<strong>Save Menu</strong>. That’s it! Now, the&nbsp;<strong>Registration</strong>&nbsp;page link will appear on your menu along with&nbsp;<strong>My Account</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also place them in the footer of your theme. Just create a secondary menu and set the display location as&nbsp;<strong>Footer Menu</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5102} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/17-footer.png" alt="Footer Menu" class="wp-image-5102"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-6-generate-user-registration-reports">Step 6. Generate User Registration Reports&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want regular reports on all the user registrations on your site, User Registration has that covered as well. You get daily, weekly, and monthly reports on how many users registered on your site, which device they used to register, and so on.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, this feature is only available in the premium version with the Extras add-on. We recommend going through&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/pricing/">User Registration’s pricing plans</a>&nbsp;to learn more about the premium version and what additional features it offers.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-2-make-custom-registration-form-in-wordpress-from-scratch-alternative-method">#2. Make Custom Registration Form in WordPress from Scratch (Alternative Method)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It’s no surprise that the default form may not be for everyone. No worries! Apart from the default form, you can create unlimited custom registration forms from scratch with User Registration.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To begin with, you need to enable&nbsp;<strong>Anyone can register</strong>&nbsp;from your General settings. Also, install and activate the&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/">User Registration</a>&nbsp;plugin on your site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the next steps, please follow the instructions below.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-1-create-a-new-user-registration-form">Step 1: Create a New User Registration Form&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the plugin installed, you’re ready to create a custom WordPress registration form. To do that, go to the&nbsp;<strong>User Registration</strong>&nbsp;tab and click on&nbsp;<strong>Add New</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":3369} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/userregistrationtoaddnew.png" alt="User Registration to Add New" class="wp-image-3369"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then, give your form a name by clicking on the pencil icon. As you can see, it already comes with the mandatory form fields:&nbsp;<strong>User Email</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>User Password</strong>&nbsp;on the right side of the form builder.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5105} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/19-name.png" alt="Default User Registration Form Fields" class="wp-image-5105"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We sidelined the explanation of the form builder in the previous section since we were dealing with the default form. So, let’s start with a short introduction to the form fields.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Fields</strong>&nbsp;tab on the left is divided into 6 sections. Among them,&nbsp;<strong>Default User Fields</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Extra Fields</strong>&nbsp;are available in the free version.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5106} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/20-add-field.png" alt="Add New User Registration Form Fields" class="wp-image-5106"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, click on the&nbsp;<strong>Add New</strong>&nbsp;button to add a row to the form.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can simply drag and drop any field you need into the blank space.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5107} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/21-drag-and-drop-min.gif" alt="Drag and Drop Fields" class="wp-image-5107"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The drag and drop feature make<s>s</s>&nbsp;changing the position of the fields just as easy&nbsp;as ABC.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5108} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/22-change-position-min.gif" alt="Field Position" class="wp-image-5108"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The form builder also lets you change the layout of the row into 2 or 3 columns. And if you need to delete a row, click on the cross icon.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5109} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/23-row-layout.png" alt="Row Layout" class="wp-image-5109"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you’ve built a complete form with all the necessary fields, hit the&nbsp;<strong>Create Form</strong>&nbsp;button.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5110} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/24-create-form.png" alt="Create Custom User Registration WordPress Form" class="wp-image-5110"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, the form&nbsp;shortcode, as well as the&nbsp;<strong>Preview</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Update Form</strong>&nbsp;buttons, appear on the top left. You can copy and paste the&nbsp;shortcode&nbsp;on any page you’d like the registration page to be displayed on.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5111} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/25-top-left-options.png" alt="Update and Preview" class="wp-image-5111"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-2-customize-your-registration-form">Step 2: Customize Your Registration Form&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the building part done, it’s time to customize your form now. Simply click on the field you want to edit, which in turn displays the&nbsp;<strong>Field Options</strong>&nbsp;of the field.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5112} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/26-field-options.png" alt="User Registration Field Options" class="wp-image-5112"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From here, you’ll be able to make changes to the&nbsp;<strong>General Settings</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Advanced Settings</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>General Settings:</strong>&nbsp;Edit the Label, Description, Placeholder, Required, and Hide Label options for form fields.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Advanced Settings:</strong>&nbsp;Add custom CSS classes, set minimum or maximum values, choose a date format, and more.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>No doubt that the&nbsp;<strong>Field Options</strong>&nbsp;are pretty easy to understand. So, you should have no problem customizing your form without a hitch.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-3-configure-registration-form-settings">Step 3. Configure Registration Form Settings&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next step is to configure the&nbsp;<strong>General Settings</strong>&nbsp;under&nbsp;<strong>Form Setting</strong>. You can set default roles, user login options, redirection URL, and so much more. You’ll find more about the&nbsp;<strong>Form Setting</strong>&nbsp;in the default form section above.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Oh, and don’t forget to&nbsp;<strong>Update Form</strong>&nbsp;to save all the changes you made.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-4-configure-user-registration-plugin-settings">Step 4. Configure User Registration Plugin Settings&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Furthermore, you can visit the User Registration’s&nbsp;<strong>Settings</strong>&nbsp;tab to make changes to the plugin itself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5113} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/27-plugin-settings.png" alt="User Registration Plugin Settings" class="wp-image-5113"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 4 tabs in the free version: General, Integration, Emails, and Import/Export.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>General:</strong>&nbsp;From here, you can restrict dashboard access plus customize My Account, login options, and front-end messages.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Integration:</strong>&nbsp;Enable spam protection for your forms with two versions of Google&nbsp;reCaptcha.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Emails:</strong>&nbsp;Customize email notifications for your registration forms and email sender options. You can also disable email notifications entirely if needed.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Import/Export:</strong>&nbsp;This setting allows you to export user data as CSV files. Plus, you can import/export forms as JSON files.&nbsp;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Make any changes you see necessary to the plugin settings, and you’re good to go.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-5-display-the-registration-form-on-a-wordpress-page">Step 5. Display the Registration Form on a WordPress Page&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, here’s the important part. You need to display the registration form you just made on your site.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All you need to do is simply add&nbsp;the&nbsp;<strong>User Registration</strong>&nbsp;block and choose the form.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Create a new page or open a page to edit. For example, we created a new page called ‘Join Us Now’. In the page editor screen, search for the&nbsp;<strong>User Registration</strong>&nbsp;block and click on it.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5116} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/31-search-block.png" alt="Search WordPress User Registration Block" class="wp-image-5116"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then, select the registration form you want to display from the dropdown.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5117} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/32-select-form.png" alt="Select User Registration Form" class="wp-image-5117"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Since the plugin comes with an in-built login form and My account page, you can display them on any page the same way.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally,&nbsp;<strong>Publish</strong>&nbsp;the user registration form to enable users to easily register on your website.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5118} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/33-publish-form.png" alt="Publish User Registration WordPress Form" class="wp-image-5118"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p id="h-alternative-way-add-user-registration-form-with-a-shortcode"><strong>Alternative Way: Add User Registration Form with a Shortcode</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also add the custom user registration form on any WordPress page by using a shortcode.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All you have to do is copy the form&nbsp;shortcode&nbsp;from the top of the form builder.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5114} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/28-shortcode.png" alt="Copy Shortcode" class="wp-image-5114"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then, head over to the page or post where you want to insert the form. In the block editor, paste the&nbsp;shortcode&nbsp;in the&nbsp;<strong>Shortcode</strong>&nbsp;block.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5115} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/29-paste-code.png" alt="Shortcode Block" class="wp-image-5115"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click&nbsp;<strong>Save Draft</strong>&nbsp;and then&nbsp;<strong>Preview</strong>&nbsp;to see how it looks.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":5119} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/30-preview-form.png" alt="Preview Custom User Registration WordPress Form" class="wp-image-5119"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, hit&nbsp;<strong>Publish</strong>&nbsp;to display the form on that specific page or post of your WordPress site.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-step-6-generate-user-registration-reports-1">Step 6. Generate User Registration Reports&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we said before, you can generate reports for every custom registration form you create on your WordPress website. You can analyze this collected data and implement the findings into your future business plans. But only as a premium member of the plugin will you be able to use this feature.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you’re interested, check out the official&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/">User Registration website</a>&nbsp;and become a premium member.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-conclusion">Conclusion&nbsp;</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That wraps up our easy guide on how to create a custom user registration form in WordPress. Yes, WordPress comes with a default user registration form. But why limit yourself to that option when there’s so much more you can do with plugins.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Creating custom user registration forms is such an easy job with a plugin like a User Registration. Even with the free version, you get a default form, sample pages, tons of form fields, and customization options.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, we highly recommend&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/">User Registration</a>&nbsp;to anyone looking to place beautiful registration forms on their website.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Registration form is just one of many types of forms. You might need forms like&nbsp;<a href="https://everestforms.net/blog/how-to-create-a-donation-form-in-wordpress/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">donation forms</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://everestforms.net/blog/wordpress-online-booking-form/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">online booking forms</a>, depending on your niche. So, we suggest going through our&nbsp;<a href="https://wpuserregistration.com/blog/">blog</a>&nbsp;to learn more through similar articles.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Also, don’t forget to share this article with your friends on social media.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Methods to Build WordPress Registration Forms ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'methods-to-build-wordpress-registration-forms', '', '', '2024-01-12 10:42:56', '2024-01-12 10:42:56', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=342', 0, 'post', '', 0),
	(343, 1, '2024-01-12 10:45:50', '2024-01-12 10:45:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have got a function which saves as stores the image from a url, the only problem is it all seems to work fine other than the image "can\'t be found"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The image and the name are in the media library but the image is broken as when you open image via url it says "not found"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Can you let me know if I have missed something.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>function set_image_from_url($url) {\n\n\n    $tmp = download_url( $url );\n\n    $file_array = array(\n        \'name\' =&gt; basename( $url ),\n        \'tmp_name\' =&gt; $tmp\n    );\n\n    /**\n     * Check for download errors\n     * if there are error unlink the temp file name\n     */\n    if ( is_wp_error( $tmp ) ) {\n        @unlink( $file_array&#91; \'tmp_name\' ] );\n        return $tmp;\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * now we can actually use media_handle_sideload\n     * we pass it the file array of the file to handle\n     * and the post id of the post to attach it to\n     * $post_id can be set to \'0\' to not attach it to any particular post\n     */\n    $post_id = \'0\';\n\n    $id = media_handle_sideload( $file_array, $post_id );\n\n    /**\n     * We don\'t want to pass something to $id\n     * if there were upload errors.\n     * So this checks for errors\n     */\n    if ( is_wp_error( $id ) ) {\n        @unlink( $file_array&#91;\'tmp_name\'] );\n        return $id;\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * No we can get the url of the sideloaded file\n     * $value now contains the file url in WordPress\n     * $id is the attachment id\n     */\n    $value = wp_get_attachment_url( $id );\n\n// Now you can do something with $value (or $id)\n\n    return $id;\n\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use : media_sideload_image wordpress function</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'save image from URL to wordpress media library', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'save-image-from-url-to-wordpress-media-library', '', '', '2024-01-12 10:45:50', '2024-01-12 10:45:50', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=343', 0, 'post', '', 0),
	(344, 1, '2024-01-12 10:48:12', '2024-01-12 10:48:12', '<!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->\n<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Table of Contents</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href="https://www.siteground.com/tutorials/wordpress/use-smtp/#How_to_configure_WordPress_to_use_your_SiteGround_email_for_sending_emails">How to configure WordPress to use your SiteGround email for sending emails</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href="https://www.siteground.com/tutorials/wordpress/use-smtp/#How_to_configure_WordPress_to_use_GoogleGmail_for_sending_emails">How to configure WordPress to use Google/Gmail for sending emails</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By default, WordPress uses the PHP Mail function to send emails. However, it is better to use&nbsp;<a href="https://www.siteground.com/kb/what-is-smtp/">SMTP</a>&nbsp;as it handles sending messages better and you can also use it to send emails from a third-party mailing service.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can watch our short video on how to configure your SMTP credentials on the server:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:embed {"url":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/CQlAAYbpXwQ","type":"rich","providerNameSlug":"embed-handler","responsive":true,"className":"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-embed-handler wp-block-embed-embed-handler wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\nhttps://www.youtube.com/embed/CQlAAYbpXwQ\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:embed -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Alternatively, follow these steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To begin, install a plugin named&nbsp;<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-mail-smtp/">WP Mail SMTP</a>&nbsp;by following the instructions in our tutorial on&nbsp;<a href="https://www.siteground.com/tutorials/wordpress/install-plugins/">how to install WordPress plugins</a>. Once the plugin is installed and activated, a new menu will show up named&nbsp;<strong>WP Mail SMTP</strong>. You will need to navigate to it to configure WordPress to work with SMTP.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":352,"width":"840px","height":"auto","sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full is-resized"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-12.png" alt="" class="wp-image-352" style="width:840px;height:auto"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On this page you will see several configuration options available:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":29534} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://d3kky1fz3fem6z.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2019/06/wp-smtp1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-29534"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here’s a list of all of them and what they configure:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>From Email</strong>&nbsp;– the email address you want to send emails from – for example, email@yourdomain.com;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>From Name</strong>&nbsp;– the name that your emails will be sent from;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Mailer</strong>&nbsp;– choose whether you want to use the&nbsp;<em>Default</em>&nbsp;PHP mail() function<em>, a Gmail/Google Workspace account, Mailgun, SendGrid</em>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<em>other SMTP servers</em>. Choosing the&nbsp;<em>Default</em>&nbsp;mode would send the messages using the PHP mail() function without SMTP authentication. The&nbsp;<em>Gmail/Google Workspace, Mailgun</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>SendGrid</em>&nbsp;options require additional info such as Client ID and Client Secret or API key that should be obtained by the respective provider. The&nbsp;<em>other SMTP server</em>&nbsp;option would prompt you to enter additional configuration details which we would describe below.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Return Path</strong>&nbsp;– check if you want to match the return path for your emails to the sending email;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you choose&nbsp;<strong><em>other SMTP servers</em></strong>&nbsp;as a mailer, you would be prompted to add the SMTP server’s configuration settings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SMTP Host</strong>&nbsp;– the IP or hostname for your SMTP server. You can find the server hostname for your SiteGround website in&nbsp;<strong>Site Tools</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Email</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Accounts</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>kebab menu</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Mail Configuration</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Manual Settings</strong>&nbsp;tab;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SMTP Port</strong>&nbsp;– the port your server works on;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Encryption</strong>&nbsp;– if you have SSL/TLS encryption available for that hostname, select it here;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Auto TLS</strong>&nbsp;– if your server supports TLS encryption, enable this option;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Authentication</strong>&nbsp;– check if your SMTP server requires authentication;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Username</strong>&nbsp;– the email address you want to send emails from – for example,&nbsp;<a href="mailto:email@yourdomain.com" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">email@yourdomainname.com</a>;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Password</strong>&nbsp;– the password for the email address you have set in the&nbsp;<strong>Username</strong>&nbsp;field;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you configure those parameters, click&nbsp;<strong>Save Settings&nbsp;</strong>at the bottom of the page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">How to configure WordPress to use your SiteGround email for sending emails</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After you install&nbsp;<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-mail-smtp/">WP Mail SMTP</a>, navigate to&nbsp;<strong>WP Mail SMTP</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Settings</strong>&nbsp;in your WordPress wp-admin panel. Select&nbsp;<strong>Other SMTP</strong>&nbsp;for the&nbsp;<strong>Mailer&nbsp;</strong>setting and a new section will open below it. Inside that new section fill in the following information:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SMTP Host</strong>&nbsp;–&nbsp;You can find the server hostname for your SiteGround website in&nbsp;<a href="https://tools.siteground.com/email"><strong>Site Tools</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Email</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Accounts</strong></a>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>kebab menu</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Mail Configuration</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Manual Settings</strong>&nbsp;tab -&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Outgoing server</strong>;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Encryption</strong>&nbsp;– TLS;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SMTP Port</strong>&nbsp;– 587;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Authentication</strong>&nbsp;– On;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SMTP Username</strong>&nbsp;– the email address you want to send emails from – for example,&nbsp;<a href="mailto:email@yourdomain.com" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">email@yourdomainname.com</a>;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Password</strong>&nbsp;– the password for the email address you have set in the SMTP&nbsp;<strong>Username</strong>&nbsp;field;</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then click the Save Settings button to apply the changes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Always test the functionality of the mail-sending service after making changes to its settings. To do that go to your WordPress admin panel -&gt;&nbsp;<strong>WP Mail SMTP</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Tools</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Email Test</strong>&nbsp;and send a test message to your email address. If you are not receiving the test message, then you need to verify the configuration settings you applied and ensure they are correct.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class="wp-block-heading">How to configure WordPress to use Google/Gmail for sending emails</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you install&nbsp;<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-mail-smtp/">WP Mail SMTP</a>, navigate to&nbsp;<strong>WP Mail SMTP</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Settings</strong>&nbsp;in your WordPress wp-admin panel. There select&nbsp;<strong>Google / Gmail&nbsp;</strong>and you will see that you require a&nbsp;<strong>Client ID</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>Client Secret</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Authorized redirect URI</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create these, go to the&nbsp;<a href="https://console.cloud.google.com/home/dashboard">Google Cloud Console Dashboard</a>&nbsp;and click on&nbsp;<strong>My Project</strong>&nbsp;at the top of the page and then&nbsp;<strong>New Project</strong>. Set desired values for&nbsp;<strong>Name</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>Organization</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Location</strong>&nbsp;and click&nbsp;<strong>Create</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then, in your Google Cloud Console sidebar, go to&nbsp;<strong>APIs &amp; Services » Library</strong>. Enter “gmail api” in the search field and click the&nbsp;<strong>Gmail API</strong>&nbsp;result. Click&nbsp;<strong>Enable</strong>, then on the new page that opens click&nbsp;<strong>Create Credentials</strong>&nbsp;at the top right of the page. Select&nbsp;<strong>Gmail API</strong>&nbsp;from the drop-down and the&nbsp;<strong>User Data</strong>&nbsp;option before clicking&nbsp;<strong>Next</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will then be asked for some basic information about your app. This information will not be shown to the public and it will be only for personal use. Fill in the following fields:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>App name</strong>&nbsp;– enter an app name of your choice</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>User support email</strong>&nbsp;– select your email address from the choices provided</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>App logo</strong>&nbsp;– you can upload a logo for the app, but it is not required</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Developer contact information</strong>&nbsp;– fill in your email address again</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click&nbsp;<strong>Save and Continue</strong>&nbsp;to proceed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can skip setting Scopes, so just click&nbsp;<strong>Save and Continue</strong>&nbsp;again.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the next page select&nbsp;<strong>Web App</strong>&nbsp;from the dropdown menu, which should make a new field&nbsp;<strong>Name</strong>&nbsp;appear. You can keep the default suggested name. Scroll down to&nbsp;<strong>Authorized Redirect URIs</strong>&nbsp;and click&nbsp;<strong>Add URI</strong>. In the field that appears input:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class="wp-block-code"><code>https:&#47;&#47;connect.wpmailsmtp.com/google/</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>and click&nbsp;<strong>Create</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once your app has been created, the&nbsp;<strong>Your Credentials</strong>&nbsp;section will expand to show you your Client ID. There’s no need to copy it now, as you’ll access it from another area in a later step.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your app will be created in&nbsp;<strong>Internal</strong>&nbsp;mode by default. In order to use it properly you need to set it to&nbsp;<strong>External</strong>&nbsp;and publish it. To do that, in your Google Cloud Console sidebar, go to&nbsp;<strong>APIs &amp; Services &gt; OAuth consent screen</strong>. Under&nbsp;<strong>User type</strong>, click on the&nbsp;<strong>MAKE EXTERNAL</strong>&nbsp;button. In the popup window that appears, select the&nbsp;<strong>In production</strong>&nbsp;option and click on&nbsp;<strong>CONFIRM</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, click on&nbsp;<strong>Credentials&nbsp;</strong>in the left-side menu. Under&nbsp;<strong>OAuth 2.0 Client IDs&nbsp;</strong>section you can see the details of the web application you just created. To view the&nbsp;<strong>Client ID</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Client Secret</strong>, click the pencil icon and on the page that opens they will be on the right side.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Copy the values of the&nbsp;<strong>Client ID</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>Client Secret</strong>&nbsp;and paste them into the corresponding fields on the WP Mail SMTP plugin Settings page. Be careful not to copy any blank spaces as this will show an error on the next steps. Click&nbsp;<strong>Save Settings</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once the page refreshes, scroll down and click the orange&nbsp;<strong>Allow plugin to send emails using your Google account</strong>&nbsp;button. This will ask you to sign in to your Google account and allow wpmailsmtp.com to access your Gmail email. Click&nbsp;<strong>Allow</strong>&nbsp;to proceed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are connecting a free Gmail account, a notice may appear, explaining that Google hasn’t verified this app. Click&nbsp;<strong>Advanced</strong>, then&nbsp;<strong>Go to wpmailsmtp.com (unsafe)</strong>&nbsp;and then click&nbsp;<strong>Allow</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have done all of the above steps correctly you will be returned to the WordPress WPMail SMTP plugin’s Settings page and a notice saying “You have successfully linked the current site with your Google API project. Now you can start sending emails through&nbsp;<a href="https://www.siteground.com/kb/gmail-smtp-server/">Gmail</a>.” will be present.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Always test the functionality of the mail-sending service after making changes to its settings. To do that go to your WordPress admin panel -&gt;&nbsp;<strong>WP Mail SMTP</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Tools</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Email Test</strong>&nbsp;and send a test message to your email address. If you are not receiving the test message, then you need to verify the configuration settings you applied and ensure they are correct.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to Configure WordPress to Use SMTP For Sending Emails', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-configure-wordpress-to-use-smtp-for-sending-emails', '', '', '2024-01-12 13:20:09', '2024-01-12 13:20:09', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=344', 0, 'post', '', 0),
	(345, 1, '2024-01-12 10:46:30', '2024-01-12 10:46:30', '<iframe title="How to Fix the WordPress Not Sending Emails Issue | Tutorial" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/CQlAAYbpXwQ?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'd592a1db0bed4f18f1d6dcb75750eca6', '', '', '2024-01-12 10:46:30', '2024-01-12 10:46:30', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/d592a1db0bed4f18f1d6dcb75750eca6/', 0, 'oembed_cache', '', 0),
	(346, 1, '2024-01-12 10:48:57', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 'Auto Draft', '', 'auto-draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2024-01-12 10:48:57', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=346', 0, 'post', '', 0),
	(347, 1, '2024-01-12 10:48:57', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 'Auto Draft', '', 'auto-draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2024-01-12 10:48:57', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=347', 0, 'post', '', 0),
	(348, 1, '2024-01-12 13:17:21', '2024-01-12 13:17:21', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For those who have a business with physical locations, embedding Google Maps on their official website is a must.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A map is the easiest way to direct users to a certain location and is also a joy to engage with when using Google Maps’ outstanding software. Developers simply have to add some lines of code to the website and Google will do its magic and list the location right away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, even though it is simple to add, encountering an unexpected error is not unthinkable. One of these errors is "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly", sometimes phrased in a slightly different way.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This error is encountered quite often, and thankfully it has some logical, easily understood explanations. Keep reading this article to find out more about it and fix it before it starts bothering your visitors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":349,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-9.png" alt="" class="wp-image-349"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Google Maps Won’t Load – Why?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Why is this error appearing in the first place? In the past, the "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly" error didn’t constitute an issue because Google ran other procedures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Later, Google changed their procedures and they are now requiring a Google API key and a Google Cloud Platform billing account to use Google Maps. This change was applied on June 11, 2018. Since then, the "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly" error seems to be encountered more and more often by those who are not aware of the change.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thus, the main cause behind this error is the API key requirement. Because Google Maps is embedded on important websites that get a lot of monthly views (over 100,000), the company thought of a method to make money by adding a fee for high-volume users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The API is still free for smaller websites that don’t get a lot of hits, but bigger websites are now charged for using the API.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When a person signs up for the API, they get a $300-worth credit to use during the first year, as well as $200-worth credit of free usage for each month. Small websites won’t normally reach these limits which lead to paying for credit. However, bigger websites will have to pay $1.60 for every 1000 views surpassing the 100,000-limit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unless your website has huge amounts of traffic and you are 100% sure that people will access the map more than 500 times a day, you can make use of Google’s API for free. If you’re not sure, you can add a maximum cap to your site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other problems related to the API are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Missing API key error – the Google Maps API does not exist</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The API key is not activated</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The API key is invalid</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The API key is not compatible with your URL</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Important Facts You Should Know About</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":350,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-10.png" alt="" class="wp-image-350"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Besides the change of procedure in 2018, you should also know some facts about Google Maps that may help you understand the appearance of the"This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly" error:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>All Google Maps projects need to have a linked billing account.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Unless a valid API key is present, the map will be displayed in a lower resolution and will have a watermark on it.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>If the credit card linked to the account is invalid or the number of free map views is surpassed, the "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly" error will show up.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Possible Fixes for "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that you know how the API works and what the requirements to use it are, it’s time to learn how to fix the error. Here are the steps for each situation in particular:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Billing</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly" error is caused by a billing problem, you, as well as the other visitors of your site, will be greeted by this message.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a website owner, you can click “Do you own this website?” and you will be redirected to the&nbsp;<a href="https://cloud.google.com/maps-platform/">Google Maps Platform</a>, where you can start making the needed changes to get the map back online.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you’ve reached the platform, you need to click “Get Started” and use Google’s wizard to fix the issue. A dialog box will show up, and you’ll have to answer a series of questions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":351,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="http://wordpress_project.test/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/image-11.png" alt="" class="wp-image-351"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://muffingroup.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/google-maps-project.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Start a new project, enable the billing option for this project (even though you won’t pay any money as long as your website respects the limits) and follow the rest of the instructions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://muffingroup.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/enable-billing.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you already have a billing account that is connected to your YouTube Red subscription or other apps in the store, the credit card information should already be there.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are creating an account for the first time, you’ll be asked to supply credit card information. Again, keep in mind that you won’t be charged if you own a small website that is very unlikely to have more than 500 hits per day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://muffingroup.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/google-maps-api-done.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The process ends here, and you can use your API key right away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading">New API Key</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you need to create a new Google API key from scratch, you will need to navigate to the&nbsp;<a href="https://cloud.google.com/maps-platform/https://cloud.google.com/maps-platform/">Google Maps Platform</a>. The process is similar to the one mentioned before, but there are some differences. You will reach this dialog box once again:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://muffingroup.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/google-maps-get-started-1.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CheckMaps, Routes, and Places and then click Continue. You want all of these options for the best user experience. Log in to your existing Google account or<a href="https://accounts.google.com/signup/v2/webcreateaccount?hl=en&amp;flowName=GlifWebSignIn&amp;flowEntry=SignUp">&nbsp;create your Google account&nbsp;</a>if you don’t own one. Just as before, start a new project and move on to the next step.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Provide your payment information, even though Google offers you&nbsp;<a href="https://cloud.google.com/maps-platform/pricing/">free credits</a>. Go to your API Console and make sure your API key can only be used on your site. You can do that by accessing Application restrictions, then navigate to “HTTP referrers” then type in your domain’s name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://muffingroup.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/google-maps-project1.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After making the necessary changes, click Save. Copy the API key because you will need it to get the map back on your website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://muffingroup.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/apikey.jpg" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your website is WordPress based, you might need to&nbsp;<a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/api-key-for-google-maps/">paste your Google API Key into a WordPress plugin</a>&nbsp;or other section of your settings. The "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly" error should now be gone.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Other Aspects to Check</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the problem still persists, you should get informed about other potential aspects that may cause the error to appear. Some of them are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Caching errors – waiting 5 to 10 minutes and refreshing the page or clearing cache data might solve the problem</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Console issues – check the console settings and look for any inconsistencies</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Final Word</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The "This Page Can\'t Load Google Maps Correctly" error is not difficult to fix, but you should stay up to date regarding any changes that Google makes to the protocol, including the billing process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Google Maps won’t load for a multitude of reasons. You need to find a solution that works best for your situation. At least one of the solutions provided above should help you fix the issue. If all else fails, it might be time to contact Google Support directly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you enjoyed reading this article, you should read these as well:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to Fix “This Page Can’t Load Google Maps Correctly”', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-fix-this-page-cant-load-google-maps-correctly', '', '', '2024-01-12 13:17:21', '2024-01-12 13:17:21', '', 0, 'http://wordpress_project.test/?p=348', 0, 'post', '', 0),
